    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-03-25T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-03-25T21:00:00-05:00" n="675"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d675">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002 Manchuria/21: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="#p_JNT1" type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-03-26T10:00:00+08:00"
                            >March 26, 1932—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 36—12:43 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your 112, March 23, 2 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>British Minister tells me that he had a talk with <persName
                            corresp="#p_STV1">T. V. Soong</persName> yesterday in the course of
                        which he endeavored to persuade him to permit <persName corresp="#p_MSFW1"
                            >Maze</persName> to reach some working agreement with customs in
                        Manchuria to tide over the situation and keep customs intact. <persName
                            corresp="#p_STV1">Soong</persName> was opposed to any such undertaking
                        saying Nanking’s decison was already taken. <persName corresp="#p_STV1"
                            >Soong</persName> asked <persName corresp="#p_LSMW1">Lampson</persName>
                        to urge his Government to make representations at Tokyo which <persName
                            corresp="#p_LSMW1">Sir Miles</persName> has done pointing out, however,
                        difficulty due to fact that we have no proof of Japanese Government’s
                        complicity in customs movement.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LSMW1">Lampson</persName>’s message went only
                        yesterday, he therefore has no knowledge of what his Government will do. He
                        tells me that <persName corresp="#p_LSRC1">Lindsay</persName>
                        <pb facs="0737" n="633" xml:id="pg_633"/> in Tokyo was somewhat discouraging
                        as to the usefulness of such action.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JNT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
